can barely pay the bills each month. How are we paying for a plane ticket to visit our family? How are we paying for anything during a LOA? Have you got any idea of the amount of paperwork-time needed to request a LOA as an international folk?

Often, people have no idea of what international PGRs go through to get to where they are, away from home. It’s been a hell of a ride, but I’d never felt so grateful and confident that I am and I’ll be okay, as long as I keep listening to myself and am in a safe(r) environment. My life and work will always serve this purpose, so others and I are safe, healthy, happy and free. n/n

I’ve developed self-care strategies, started practicing boundaries and compassion towards myself and others - super difficult but amazingly worth it. I’ve explored my identity, started un-learning and re-learning a lot. Explored trust: beautiful, fragile yet so powerful 15/n

I started getting the help I’d been needing for so long. We’ll need to pause it because we can’t keep affording the costs for now… but I am confident that the tools I’ve got in these past years are enough for me to live a much healthier life, and all humans deserve that! 14/n

Despite paying a lot of money for access to the NHS as a Tier 4 visa holder, I didn’t have access to mental health care; the “support” that I got at IAPT (after a 1year waiting list) made my symptoms worse. Through an extreme family effort and investing a lot of my paycheck 13/n

Despite having a rough time growing up, I am very privileged. How normalised are inequity and oppression that we consider access to education, water, housing or nutritious meals a privilege, let alone access to mental health care?!?! 12/n

Because mental health is still underrated and understudied, specially prevention of mental illness with an intersectional approach. Because we live in an ableist White-human-centered heteronormative world that’s making the planet ill and we’re running out of time to treat it 11/n

that I could only have nice things and a nice life if I overworked, were perfect, didn’t make mistakes o rested, and if I didn’t do that, I wouldn’t be worth of respect and love - and all that is wrong. Because *resilience* is glorified in a world of exploitation and abuse. 10/n

Because nobody had told me those violent thoughts in my head when I get angry are natural and actually healthy and I lived guilty and scared of myself my whole life. Because looking after myself also means asking for help, which doesn’t mean I’m not enough. Because I learnt 9/n

Why am I (over)sharing all this? Because I wish someone had shared this type of experiences when I was growing up. I wish I’d had role models to look up to who showed human, imperfect, vulnerable and compassionate because now I have to do the reparenting work all by myself 8/n

I was reprimanded for being “too smart”, “too direct”, “too sensitive”, “too tomboy” or “too intense”. Family and teachers would ask me why I’d be “so rude” if I was actually a “nice girl” - turns out I am neurodivergent, queer, enby, HSP and most likely have ADHD. 7/n

I’ve reprocessed the intense bullying I experienced through my childhood - my first suicidal thoughts popped up when I was in elementary school. Back then I used to hit myself and punch the wall cause I felt so overwhelmed with emotions I didn’t know how to manage or express 6/n

I’ve also worked on the trauma of being a high performance athlete and its toxic environment - I started training at the age of 2! I’ve worked on being sexually harrassed in the streets in Mex ever since I can remember, and being hypervigilant to avoid being robbed/kidnapped 5/n

I’ve also reprocessed the sudden and inexplicable death of my best friend when we were 20; a car crash which left me partially epileptic (now I can watch car scenes without having flashbacks!); the 2017 earthquake in Mexico which we conmemorate today, tho I’m still jumpy 4/n

EMDR and Nutritional Therapy have helped me radically, yet the price has been high economically, emotionally, physically and mentally. Through EMDR I’ve reprocessed child neglection; grieved the loss of my dad, which I didn’t know I needed to cause he died when I was 2yo. 3/n

I’ve cPTSD and hadn’t realised how much it’d impacted my existence until I started healing and noticing new authentic different responses in me; physical, emotional, mental and spiritual. It’s like the first time one wears glasses and discovers a whole new reality. 2/n

CW: grief, violence, harrassment, mental health

blankly into space and seem like daydreaming (which I guess might be hard to identify because I daydream a lot!). If this happens, just let one come back to Earth by themself and give them some time and reassurance after because one can feel disoriented/confused. I took some 6/

myoclonic seizures and there’s nothing much one can do other than let them be and go away. I’ve also experienced absence seizures and if one’s “lucky” enough to realise one had it, it feels like some frames had been cut out from your mind’s film. If this happens I might stare 5/

and I usually feel tired when this happens. Sometimes one of my arms (or a limb) suddenly jumps, which is annoying if I’m writing, holding a cuppa or even mixing, but no biggie. If I’m too stressed my head twitches violently (this one hurts badly!). All these are called 4/

earthquake, but it’s actually me being tremory in the inside, it’s barely perceptible to others if they pay close attention to my hands. I also get this if I don’t sleep and when I have an adrenaline rush (both positve or negative). Sometimes it lasts seconds, sometimes days 3/

My type of epilepsy is known as Complex Partial Seizures, Partial Epilepsy, or Focal Epilepsy. It’s localised in my frontal and left lobes, we think it was caused by a car accident 12 years ago. It’s common for me to wake up in the middle of the night feeling like there’s an 2/
